Follow below steps for Homework 1:

1. Ensure that you are subscribed to the course mailing list.
   http://mailman.depaul.edu/mailman/listinfo/csc301aut15/

2. Download and install Oracle Java 8 SDK. 
     http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/jdk8-downloads-2133151.html

3. Download and install Git client software.
   A. Windows: install Git for Windows
               https://github.com/git-for-windows/git/releases
               http://git-for-windows.github.io/

      i. If installing to your own machine with administrator rights, get
           Git-2.5.2-32-bit.exe
             or
           Git-2.5.2-64-bit.exe

      ii. If installing without administrator rights, get
           PortableGit-2.5.2-32-bit.7z.exe
             or
           PortableGit-2.5.2-64-bit.7z.exe
   B. OS X: install Git for the Mac platform
            http://git-scm.com/download/mac
   C. Linux: install using your package manager, e.g., sudo apt-get install git

4. Download and install Eclipse IDE for Java Developers (32 bit or 64 bit)
   http://www.eclipse.org/downloads/installer.php

5. To simplify access to the common Git operations, activate the Git toolbar
   by selecting the Window menu + Perspective + Customize perspective...
   In Customize perspective window go to Action Set Availability tab and
   check the Git and the Git Navigation Actions entries.

6. To clone this project locally and work on it using eclipse, import this project
   by selecting the File menu + Import...
   In Import window under Git choose Projects from Git and click Next
   Choose Clone URI and click Next
   Copy and paste Bitbucket clone string into URI and proceed
   
   You can access the Bitbucket clone string from your Bitbucket homepage
   select this project and on the top left side click on "..." to see actions.
   Choose clone from the list and clone string will already be highlighted.
   Copy and paste into URI textbox in Eclipse and proceed
   
7. There are 10 methods you will need to implement.
   Read every file and complete the methods with TODO comments.

8. On Saturday, I will be releasing a JUnit test file, it will be on Bitbucket.
   Pull that file using the pull button on the Eclipse Toolbar.
   
9. Make sure that your code passes all the tests in this test file.

10. Commit and push your code into Bitbucket and verify your submission 
    by checking the online repository.

If you have any questions, send them to the emailing list.
    
Good Luck!